Question :- 4 

How does maintaining selectedIndex using setState in the parent widget differ from
managing it through a Provider? What specific problem arises when setState alone is used and a
promotional push notification deep-links the customer directly into the Cart tab?

Ans :-

-> In this e-commerce app, the BottomNavigationBar has four tabs: Home, Search, Cart, and Profile.

-> If I use setState, the selectedIndex is stored only in the parent widget. When the user taps a tab, setState updates the index and the screen changes.
This method is simple and works well for small apps.

-> If I use Provider, the selectedIndex is stored in a shared state. 
Any widget in the app can read or change the selected tab without passing data through many widgets. 
This is better for larger apps because the navigation state is available everywhere.

-> The problem with using setState only happens when the app receives a promotional push notification that opens the Cart tab directly. 
Since selectedIndex is only stored inside one widget, the app may still open with the default Home tab instead of the Cart tab.
The navigation state is not shared, so it is difficult for other parts of the app to change the selected tab.

-> With Provider, the notification handler can update the shared selectedIndex to the Cart tab before the screen is shown. 
The app will open directly on the Cart page, giving the user the correct experience.
